      <details>
        <summary>Is the Big Five more scientifically valid than the MBTI?</summary>
        <p>Yes. The Big Five model is widely regarded as the most scientifically robust personality framework available. It was derived from decades of factor-analytic research across cultures and languages, and it consistently replicates in independent studies. The MBTI has faced criticism for issues with test-retest reliability, binary categories instead of continuous scales, and limited predictive validity compared to the Big Five. Most academic personality research uses the Big Five rather than the MBTI.</p>
      </details>
